            "type": "assistant",
            "text": "---\n\n# Critical Architectural Review: `sonar-sim`\n\n## Overall Impression\n\nThis is a well-structured simulation engine. Clean layering, good test coverage, disciplined visibility control. The crate does one thing — simulate Solana transactions locally via LiteSVM — and it does it with clear separation of concerns. That said, there are real structural issues that will compound as the crate grows.\n\n---\n\n## What's Done Well\n\n**Visibility discipline.** The `pub(crate)` + re-export pattern in `lib.rs` is textbook. Internal modules can be freely reorganized without breaking downstream consumers. The public surface is explicitly curated — this is rare and commendable.\n\n**Trait-based extensibility.** `AccountSource`, `FetchPolicy`, `FetchObserver`, `RpcAccountProvider` — these are clean seams. They make the fetching pipeline testable without real RPC, and the tests prove it works (fake providers, counting providers, deny-all policies, recording observers).\n\n**Test quality.** Every module has focused unit tests with purpose-built test doubles. No shared test fixtures leaking across modules. The test doubles are scoped tightly to `#[cfg(test)]` blocks. The coverage of edge cases (negative cache, repeated missing keys, closed accounts) shows real operational experience baked in.\n\n**Backend isolation.** `ReturnData` and `SimulationMetadata` exist as sonar-sim's own types rather than re-exporting `litesvm::types`. This means swapping the SVM backend wouldn't ripple through the public API.\n\n---\n\n## Structural Issues\n\n### 1. `executor.rs` is a God Module (~820 lines, 7+ distinct concerns)\n\nThis file contains:\n- Builtin program ID constants and predicates (`LITESVM_BUILTIN_PROGRAM_IDS`, `is_litesvm_builtin_program`, `is_native_or_sysvar`)\n- `SignatureVerification` enum\n- `ExecutionOptions`, `StateMutationOptions`, `SimulationOptions`, `SimulationOptionsBuilder` — the entire options hierarchy\n- `AppliedRecord`\n- Five pipeline step functions (`load_accounts`, `apply_replacements`, `apply_data_patches`, `apply_slot`, `apply_timestamp`)\n- `TransactionExecutor` — the core execution engine\n- `SimulationResult`, `ExecutionStatus`\n- `convert_metadata` — the LiteSVM adapter\n- `account_priority` — ordering logic\n- An `impl ResolvedAccounts` block (line 488) that belongs in `types/resolved.rs`\n\nThis violates the Single Responsibility Principle. The options hierarchy, the pipeline steps, the builtin program knowledge, and the executor itself are four distinct concerns sharing one file.\n\n**Concrete impact:** The `impl ResolvedAccounts` for `lookup_details()` at line 488 is defined in `executor.rs` instead of `types/resolved.rs`. This creates a confusing orphan impl — someone reading `resolved.rs` won't know this method exists.\n\n### 2. Circular Dependency Between `account_fetcher` and `executor`\n\n`account_fetcher.rs:92` calls `crate::is_litesvm_builtin_program(key)` — a function defined in `executor.rs`. This creates a backward dependency from a lower-level module (fetching) to a higher-level module (execution). The fetcher shouldn't need to know about the executor.\n\nThe fix is simple: move `LITESVM_BUILTIN_PROGRAM_IDS`, `EXTRA_NATIVE_SYSVAR_IDS`, `is_litesvm_builtin_program`, and `is_native_or_sysvar` into their own leaf module (e.g., `program_ids.rs` or `known_programs.rs`). Both `account_fetcher` and `executor` import from it. Clean DAG restored.\n\n### 3. `ResolvedAccounts` Has No Encapsulation\n\n```rust\npub struct ResolvedAccounts {\n    pub accounts: HashMap\u003cPubkey, AccountSharedData\u003e,\n    pub lookups: Vec\u003cResolvedLookup\u003e,\n}\n```\n\nBoth fields are `pub`. Every consumer directly reaches in — `resolved.accounts.get(...)`, `resolved.accounts.contains_key(...)`, `resolved.accounts.insert(...)`. This means:\n\n- No invariant can ever be enforced on the account set\n- You can't add indexing, lazy loading, or validation without touching every call site\n- The `funding/mod.rs` pattern of `extras: HashMap\u003cPubkey, AccountSharedData\u003e` as a side-channel (lines 29, 46-51) exists because there's no clean way to stage accounts into a `ResolvedAccounts` without mutating it directly\n\nThis is the most load-bearing type in the crate and it's a transparent bag of data.\n\n### 4. The `extras` Side-Channel in `funding/mod.rs` Is a Code Smell\n\n`prepare_single_token_funding` takes `extras: \u0026mut HashMap\u003cPubkey, AccountSharedData\u003e` alongside `resolved: \u0026ResolvedAccounts`. The `lookup_account` helper (line 45) tries `resolved` first, then `extras`. `ensure_account_loaded` (line 213) creates a temporary `ResolvedAccounts`, calls `append_accounts`, then moves the results into `extras`.\n\nThis is effectively a two-tier lookup with manual plumbing — it exists because `prepare_token_fundings` receives a `\u0026ResolvedAccounts` (immutable) but may need to fetch additional accounts. The design would be cleaner if either:\n- `ResolvedAccounts` had an `extend` method and the function received `\u0026mut ResolvedAccounts`\n- Or a dedicated `AccountResolver` abstraction handled the layered lookup\n\n### 5. Builder Pattern on `SimulationOptions` Is Low-Value\n\nThe builder (lines 116-165) consumes `self` on every call but adds no validation in `build()`. It's a 1:1 mapping of struct fields. The struct itself already derives `Default` and has `pub` fields, so callers can just do struct literal with `..Default::default()`. The builder adds 50 lines of code with zero added safety or ergonomics.\n\n### 6. Error Type Is Stringly-Typed\n\nAlmost every variant carries a `reason: String`. There's no structured information beyond the variant discriminant and an optional `Pubkey`. This makes programmatic error handling nearly impossible for consumers. For example, `SonarSimError::Token { account: Some(key), reason: \"...\" }` — a consumer can't distinguish \"mint not found\" from \"wrong program owner\" without parsing the string.\n\nThe `reason` strings are also inconsistent — sometimes they include the full chain (`\"Failed to prepare token funding for {}: {e}\"`), sometimes just the immediate cause. This isn't catastrophic for a simulation library, but it limits downstream composability.\n\n### 7. `AccountAppender` Trait Leaks `ResolvedAccounts`\n\n```rust\npub trait AccountAppender {\n    fn append_accounts(\u0026mut self, resolved: \u0026mut ResolvedAccounts, pubkeys: \u0026[Pubkey]) -\u003e Result\u003c()\u003e;\n}\n```\n\nThis trait couples every implementor to `ResolvedAccounts`. If the trait were `fn fetch(\u0026mut self, pubkeys: \u0026[Pubkey]) -\u003e Result\u003cHashMap\u003cPubkey, AccountSharedData\u003e\u003e`, callers could decide where to put the results. The current design forces the \"append into this specific struct\" pattern, which is why `ensure_account_loaded` in funding has to create a temporary `ResolvedAccounts` and drain it.\n\n### 8. No Integration Tests\n\nEvery test is a unit test inside `#[cfg(test)]` blocks. There's no `tests/` directory with end-to-end scenarios (e.g., \"parse raw transaction -\u003e load accounts -\u003e prepare fundings -\u003e execute -\u003e compute balance changes\"). The individual modules are well-tested in isolation, but the full pipeline wiring is untested.\n\n---\n\n## Minor Issues\n\n**Duplicated test helpers.** `system_account()`, `make_token_account()`, `create_transfer_transaction()` are copy-pasted across 4+ test modules with slight variations. A shared `test_utils` module (behind `#[cfg(test)]`) would reduce drift.\n\n**`FakeAccountProvider` is pub.** It's exported from the crate's public API (`lib.rs:49`). A test utility exposed as part of the stable API. If this is intentional (for downstream test support), it should be documented. If not, it should be behind a `test-utils` feature flag.\n\n**`format_pubkeys` is `pub(crate)` but defined in `account_fetcher`.** It's used by `account_loader`. It's a utility function that doesn't belong to either module — it belongs in a shared `fmt` or `util` module.\n\n**`serde::Serialize` only on some types.** `SolBalanceChange` and `TokenBalanceChange` derive `Serialize`, but `SimulationResult`, `SimulationMetadata`, and `ExecutionStatus` don't. If consumers need to serialize results, they have to map to their own types. The derive decisions seem ad-hoc rather than policy-driven.\n\n**`raw_to_ui_amount` guard for `factor == 0.0`.** On line 144 of `token_decode.rs`, the check `if factor == 0.0` can never trigger because `10f64.powi(n)` for any valid `u8` is never zero. Dead code that suggests defensive programming without understanding the domain.\n\n---\n\n## Dependency Surface\n\n18 direct dependencies is manageable for a Solana simulation crate, but the dual dependency on `spl-token` (v9) and `spl-token-2022` (v10) deserves attention. These pull in their own Solana SDK dependencies and can create version conflicts. The crate already leverages the shared base layout between the two — consider whether `spl-token-2022` can be dropped for the base decoding path and only used where extensions are genuinely needed (i.e., `funding/token2022.rs`).\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Recommendations (by impact)\n\n| Priority | Issue | Recommendation |\n|----------|-------|----------------|\n| High | `executor.rs` god module | Extract `known_programs.rs`, `options.rs`, `pipeline.rs`; move orphan `impl ResolvedAccounts` to `resolved.rs` |\n| High | Circular dep fetcher→executor | Move builtin program IDs to a leaf module |\n| Medium | `ResolvedAccounts` is a transparent bag | Add accessor methods, make fields `pub(crate)` |\n| Medium | `extras` side-channel in funding | Redesign `AccountAppender` or pass `\u0026mut ResolvedAccounts` |\n| Medium | No integration tests | Add `tests/` directory with full pipeline scenarios |\n| Low | Duplicated test helpers | Shared `test_utils` module |\n| Low | `FakeAccountProvider` in public API | Feature-gate or document |\n| Low | Unused builder pattern | Consider removing in favor of struct literals |\n\nThe crate is in good shape for its current scope. The issues above are the kind that hurt when the crate grows — when new team members onboard, when new SVM backends arrive, when consumers try to compose with the error types. Addressing the top two (god module, circular dep) would be the highest-leverage cleanup.",
